source_text:
There is a deep parallel between the Zel’dovich reconstruction of the upper $E\rightarrow 0$ part of the Coulomb spectrum in the $r_{0}\ll a_{B}$ limit and the low-energy scattering by a short-range potential well. For a particle of energy $E=\hbar^{2}k^{2}/2m$ whose wave vector k is small in magnitude, $kr_{0}\ll 1$ , scattered by the short-range potential $U_{s}(r)$ vanishing for $r>r_{0}$ the scattering length $a_{s}$ can be defined (20) through the $k\rightarrow 0$ limit of the relationship 

 $1/ka_{s}=-\cot\delta_{s}(k)$  (13) 
 where $\delta_{s}(k)$ is the phase shift. Employing Seaton’s theorem (9) $\delta=\pi\mu$ relating the quantum defect to the zero-energy phase shift it is straightforward to realize that Eqs.( 12 ) and ( 13 ) are direct analogs. The Coulomb field is characterized by its own length scale, the Bohr radius $a_{B}$ . Its free particle counterpart entering Eq.( 13 ) is the de Broglie wavelength $2\pi/k$ . The range of applicability of Eq.( 12 ) $r_{0}\ll a_{B}

suspicious_text:
The contribution stemming from $\hat{H}_{1}(k)$ has been effectively bounded, yielding the following inequality:

\begin{equation}
\displaystyle|\mathcal{H}^{n,l}_{1,z}(x)|\leq\begin{cases}\eqref{e:term-Bound-H1-line}&\text{ for }n=0,\\
\eqref{e:term-Bound-H1-bubble-bound}&\text{ for }n=1,\\
\eqref{e:term-toBound-H1-triangle-t1-bound}+\eqref{e:term-toBound-H1-triangle-t2-bound}&\text{ for }n=2.\end{cases} \tag{3.71}
\end{equation}

Here, the sum of equation numbers signifies the summation of the respective terms on the right-hand sides of those equations. Notably, when $z=z_{I}$, this bound invokes $I_{n+2,l}(x)$ and consequently cannot be applied for $d=d_{c}+1,d_{c}+2$. Despite the availability of alternative bounds, we have elected to utilize these specific bounds due to their superior numerical performance.

The symbol $(f \otimes g)(x)$ is employed below to signify that the paths associated with $f$ are entirely distinct from those of $g$. As an illustration, $(G_{n,z} \otimes G_{m,z})(x)$ corresponds to a configuration where the path utilized in $G_{n,z}$ does not intersect with that of $G_{m,z}$. We introduce $a_{n}(x)$ as the count of $n$-step simple random walks originating from $0$ and terminating at $x$, with the constraint that no bond is traversed more than once. It is notable that $(a_{n} \otimes a_{m})(x) \leq a_{n+m}(x)$. Moreover, $(a_{n} \otimes G_{m,z})(x)$ denotes the conjunction of an $n$-step SRW path, as accounted for in $a_{n}$, and a percolation path of maximum length $m$. Here, given the $n$-step SRW path, $G_{m,z}(x)$ quantifies the probability of an occupied percolation path existing that exclusively employs bonds distinct from those used in the SRW. The subsequent bounds, which underpin our analysis, hold true for all models under consideration:

\begin{equation}
G

